To combat this, the FPA Tunisia seeks to improve the sexual and reproductive health of young women and men through enhanced access to sexual health services and information.

Since 2009, FPA Tunisia has coached youth councils made up of fifty youths who distribute information and pamphlets in schools and universities. The youth councils also developed mobile applications and an online platform that allow young people to send in anonymous questions about sexuality. FPA Tunisia holds meetings in various municipalities to engage with young women and men while they are still in school, so that they have the necessary tools to protect themselves before they close the door to sexual education.

Based on a motherhood-centric approach, feminist leaders in Malawi have been fighting against a constitutional amendment which called for the reduction of sex education to just one form: abstinence. If the bill had been proposed, sexual health education focussing only on the importance of abstinence services would have resulted in negative health outcomes for girls and women.

FPA Malawi believes information is the key to success. After its initial submission in 2010, FPA continued to work with women’s rights organisations, community leaders and national and international members to promote the need to amend the law.
